AB  - The proceedings contain 45 papers. The special focus in this conference is on Principles and Practice of Multi-Agent Systems. The topics include: On the Role of Causal Reasoning in Autonomous Agents and Multi-Agent Systems; agent-Based Cyclist Model for Shared Space Traffic Simulation; XAI-Guided Feature Pruning for Deep Reinforcement Learning in EV Routing Problems; ABA Disputes in ASP: Advancing Argument Games Through Multi-shot Solving; from Explicit Allowances to Defeasible Deontic Operators: A Modal View; Deep Learning-Enhanced Multi-agent Architecture for Real-Time UAM Trajectory Prediction and Collision Risk Assessment; preface; predicting the Outcome of Ongoing Automated Negotiations; agent-Based Simulation of a Financial Market with Large Language Models; strategyproof Matching with Maximum and Minimum Quotas for Two Types of Members; Building LLM-Based Artificial Market Simulations: Can LLMs Function as Agents in Multi-agent Simulations for Finance?; Metric Distortion of STV on the Line and the Impact of Voter Turnout; symbolic Representation for Graded Dynamic Epistemic Logic; language Model-Driven Agent-Based Framework for Generating and Evaluating Cyber Attack Scenarios; questions About Quantities: Epistemic Numerical Estimate Aggregation; Solving Dec-POMDPs as POMDPs Using Imitation Learning; towards Neuro-Symbolic Conceptual Blending; modular Successor Representations for Transfer Learning in Social Navigation; HMCF: A Human-in-the-Loop Multi-robot Collaboration Framework Based on Large Language Models; strategic Agent-Based Equilibrium Models for Urban Mobility: The Traffic Filter Location Problem; adaptive Multi-round Influence Maximization with Limited Information; OSP Diffusion Auctions; influence Maximization in Unknown Social Networks: A Contextual Bandit Approach (Extended Abstract); tableaux for Epistemic Gödel Logic; a Modal Logic for Temporal and Jurisdictional Classifier Models; A Mission-Aware Coordinated Adaptation Mechanism for Enhancing Resilience of EO Satellite Constellations; Effective Use of LLMs via Counterfactual Reasoning for Transparent Recommendation Explanations; MiCRO for Multilateral Negotiations; Integrating Cognitive Reasoning Into Medical Scheduling: a Transition from ASP Personas to L-DINF Agents; AOAD-MAT: Transformer-Based Multi-agent Deep Reinforcement Learning Model Considering Agents’ Order of Action Decisions.
