TY  - CONF
TI  - Towards maintenance 4.0: Deep learning and LLM-driven bearings fault detection
AU  - Bouchra, A.
AU  - Tabaa, M.
AU  - Batal, M.
AU  - Elmahjoub, A.A.
T2  - AIP Conference Proceedings
AB  - The maintenance industrial landscape is changing with the integration of new emerging technologies, such as Deep Learning (DL) and Large Language Models (LLMs), for setting up predictive strategies. This paper discusses the emerging paradigm in the context of predictive maintenance, signifying its importance toward improving equipment reliability, reducing unplanned downtime, and providing ways for cost savings on maintenance through proactive failure prediction. This is a brief review of state-of-the-art predictive maintenance role-plays of DL in analyzing sensor data for early fault detection and, at the same time, leveraging LLMs for the translation of complex diagnostic data into actionable maintenance recommendations. Along with the positive progress in the broad application of these technologies, the implementation has had to face several data integration complexities, model customizations, and a must around human-AI interaction with imperatives. Future important areas for research and development in this regard entail advancements in AI and machine learning algorithms, integration of IoT and sensor technologies with development, and human-AI maintenance, regulations, and ethics of collaborative frameworks. This paper presents an overview of the present achievements and outlines a road map of the efforts that pave a way for overcoming the existing challenges for the realization of Maintenance 4.0. In this paper, it is indicated how the integration of DL and LLMs can become a game-changer in current predictive maintenance practices, deriving from the future trends and the continued evolutions of respective industrial strategies. © 2025 Author(s).
