TY  - JOUR
TI  - Technological framework and service model of information search in smart libraries:A generative artificial intelligence perspective
AU  - Zhao, Y.
AU  - Fu, Z.
AU  - Zeng, P.
AU  - Li, J.
T2  - Journal of Library Science in China
AB  - With the rapid advancement of generative artificial intelligence GenAI technologies users’ information needs and information behaviours have become markedly diversified and complex. Traditional information retrieval paradigms which rely on static index matching and passive response now struggle to satisfy expectations for contextual accuracy multimodal interaction and real-time relevance. Smart libraries must therefore shift from ‟passive response to ‟proactive engagement and transition from ‟static adaptation to ‟ dynamic service. By harnessing the natural language processing multimodal fusion and knowledge-generation capacities of large language models LLMs GenAI offers a decisive technological basis for developing personalized precise and adaptive information search services. This paper first reviews the functional evolution of library search through three paradigm—conventional keyword retrieval semantic retrieval and GenAI-driven generative retrieval—clarifying the transformation of resource organization query formulation and result presentation. It then drawing on the Computers Are Social Actors CASA paradigm and a sociotechnical system perspective proposes an LLM Agent framework that orchestrates intention perception knowledge sourcing reasoning-based generation and feedback refinement. This framework supports human-AI cognitive co-construction across multiple smart library scenarios enabling users to move iteratively from vague information intentions to structured knowledge representations through conversational guidance and retrieval-augmented generation. Scenario analysis focuses on five core services widely adopted in Chinese smart library practices—reference consulting services resource discovery knowledge services reading promotion and information literacy training. Aligning each scenario with the classical four information service elements—users providers contents and strategies—the study develops three adaptive paths for GenAI-driven information search high affinity scenarios where LLMs serve as the primary engine to deliver real-time conversational retrieval and personalized recommendation structure fusion scenarios where LLM Agents integrate with knowledge graphs and vector repositories to support semantic reasoning cross-document synthesis and trend analysis and auxiliary embedding scenarios where GenAI supplements existing systems by generating adaptive reading lists cross-modal accessibility outputs and personalized training feedback while respecting established service logic. Implementation is addressed through a three-layer approach multi-source data construction domain-specific instruction tuning reinforced by retrieval-augmented and knowledge graph-augmented generation and scene-oriented deployment via plug-in agents which calibrate model parameters according to scenario-specific interaction needs. Due to the prohibitive costs of local fine-tuning the paper advocates a collaborative platform-based model. In this model national or regional ‟library LLM hubs provide participating institutions with shared application interfaces and low-code agent components. By shifting library information services from instrumental interaction to collaborative cognition the proposed framework strengthens the evolution of smart libraries from tool-oriented infrastructures to cognitive gain-oriented ecosystems. The framework offers a coherent blueprint for data engineering model refinement and service orchestration. It contributes conceptual clarity and practical guidance to the future construction of smart library knowledge search infrastructures. 3 figs. 2 tabs. 37 refs. © 2025, Editorial Office of Journal of Library Science in China. All rights reserved.
