TY  - JOUR
TI  - LLM-driven adaptive security for the internet of energy (IoE)
AU  - Halgamuge, M.N.
T2  - IEEE Network
AB  - The Internet of Energy (IoE) integrates renewable energy generators, smart-grid controllers, and extensive sensor networks, creating a highly dynamic attack surface that traditional signature-based intrusion detection systems (IDSs) often fail to secure. We propose a synergistic, two-tier Large Language Model (LLM)-driven adaptive security architecture: a 22-million-parameter MiniLM deployed at the edge converts enriched flow telemetry into physics-aware “sentences” for context-sensitive alerting, while a cloud-based GPT-4 assistant performs forensic analysis, automatically generates Snort rules, and sends reinforcement signals back to the edge. This cooperative edge-cloud orchestration, evaluated on the UNSW-NB15 dataset (82,000 flows), improves the F<inf>1</inf> score to 0.889, reduces false positives from 68% to 26%, and, in human-in-the-loop exercises, enables GPT-4 explanations to reduce mean time-to-contain by 41%, all within a 0.20-second latency budget. Ablation studies demonstrate that role-aware encoding yields marginal but beneficial improvements to performance. Our study demonstrates that edge-deployed LLMs can outperform traditional monitoring methods without exceeding operational constraints; that hybrid edge–cloud systems deliver actionable intelligence from IoE network telemetry; and that adaptive, explainable generative AI defenses significantly enhance IoE cybersecurity resilience. Future research directions include adversarially robust prompting, federated fine-tuning, and formal safety assurance for critical infrastructure defense. © 1986-2012 IEEE.
