TY  - CONF
TI  - Gaze-enhanced and LLM-enabled system for intuitive human-robot collaboration
AU  - Liang, X.
AU  - Rivera, J.C.
AU  - Cai, J.
AU  - Li, S.
AB  - Deploying collaborative robots in human-involved scenarios, notably in construction, requires intuitive human-robot collaboration (HRC) to improve efficiency and safety. Current collaborative robots often rely on human operators for planning, requiring extensive knowledge of robot control. This study proposes a gaze-enhanced and large language model (LLM)-enabled method to foster human-like collaboration in HRC, enhancing intuitive interaction and operational effectiveness. First, it allows workers to instruct robots intuitively using natural language coupled with gaze. Second, it extends robot motion planning by sequentially understanding context and planning tasks. By integrating gaze with an LLM (i.e., ChatGPT), the system accurately interprets human requirements, enhancing the transparency and effectiveness of HRC. In the demonstration, a participant interacted with a collaborative robot to identify and plan parts retrieval from multiple similar-appearing items. This research underscores the potential of gaze and LLM technologies in overcoming existing HRC barriers and contributes to making HRC more intuitive and efficient in construction. © ASCE.
