AB  - The proceedings contain 18 papers. The special focus in this conference is on Human Computation and Crowdsourcing. The topics include: How Crowd Worker Factors Infuence Subjective Annotations: A Study of Tagging Misogynistic Hate Speech in Tweets; Collect, Measure, Repeat: Reliability Factors for Responsible AI Data Collection; where Does My Model Underperform? A Human Evaluation of Slice Discovery Algorithms; a Task-Interdependency Model of Complex Collaboration Towards Human-Centered Crowd Work (Extended Abstract); task as Context: A Sensemaking Perspective on Annotating Inter-Dependent Event Attributes with Non-Experts; BackTrace: A Human-AI Collaborative Approach to Discovering Studio Backdrops in Historical Photographs; Rethinking Quality Assurance for Crowdsourced Multi-ROI Image Segmentation; accounting for Transfer of Learning Using Human Behavior Models; A Taxonomy of Human and ML Strengths in Decision-Making to Investigate Human-ML Complementarity; characterizing Time Spent in Video Object Tracking Annotation Tasks: A Study of Task Complexity in Vehicle Tracking; Humans Forgo Reward to Instill Fairness into AI; Does Human Collaboration Enhance the Accuracy of Identifying LLM-Generated Deepfake Texts?; a Cluster-Aware Transfer Learning for Bayesian Optimization of Personalized Preference Models; confdence Contours: Uncertainty-Aware Annotation for Medical Semantic Segmentation; A Crowd–AI Collaborative Approach to Address Demographic Bias for Student Performance Prediction in Online Education.
