AB  - Systematic literature reviews (SLRs) are becoming increasingly time-consuming due to the rapid growth of scientific publications. Modern artificial intelligence—based tools, especially large language models (LLM), make it possible to automate individual review stages, from screening to data synthesis. The article examines more than 20 sources and suggests a classification of such solutions according to four parameters. Comparative metrics (F1, recall) are given, and key limitations are discussed: hallucinations, reproducibility, and domain adaptation. The work is aimed at researchers who introduce AI into the practice of evidence-based analysis.
