AU  - Guo, Ying
T3  - Aicss '25
AB  - With the rapid advancement of large language models (LLMs), machine translation (MT) could deliver more fluent and context-aware outputs than earlier approaches. Nevertheless, the LLM-based MT still needs to compensated in scientific translation including specialized terminology, logical density, and stylistic complexity. This study uses both automatic evaluation (BLEU) and manual assessment to evaluate the quality of English-to-Chinese LLM-based MT based on a source text from a national scientific translation contest, with five human translations adopted as references, which shows that the MT output achieved an overall BLEU score close to 70, suggesting relatively high lexical accuracy. However, sentence-level analysis revealed substantial variation, with long and stylistically nuanced sentences scoring as low as 11 in automatic metrics but up to 75 in human judgment, reflecting the limitations of reference-based evaluation and the persistent challenges of LLM-based MT in handling discourse and style. The findings indicate that while LLM-based MT demonstrates strong potential for scientific translation, but it has not yet reached the level to fully replace human translators. Instead, human-machine collaboration could be a more effective way to ensure its efficiency, accuracy and contextual appropriateness at the same time. The study could provide an empirical evidence for the LLM-based MT evaluation of scientific texts.
