T3  - Eki '25
AB  - With the rapid advancement of artificial intelligence and large language models (LLMs), their application in specialized translation services has become increasingly prominent. This study evaluates the translation performance of four leading LLMs—ChatGPT-o1, ChatGPT-o3-mini-high, DeepSeek-R1, and Qwen-2.5—in translating political texts between Chinese and English, utilizing the United Nations Parallel Corpus as a benchmark. Employing quantitative metrics including BLEU, chrF++, and BERTScore, the analysis provides a comprehensive assessment of each model's ability to handle the nuanced terminology and complex sentence structures characteristic of political discourse.The results indicate significant performance differences among the models, with ChatGPT-o1 demonstrating superior lexical and semantic accuracy, closely followed by Qwen-2.5 and DeepSeek-R1. In contrast, ChatGPT-o3-mini-high exhibited relatively weaker performance, reflecting its limitations in effectively translating intricate political texts. A consistent performance gap was observed, with all models performing notably better in Chinese-to-English translations compared to English-to-Chinese translations.This research provides a decision-support basis for service consumers (e.g., translators or organizations) in selecting models for sensitive translation tasks and offers practical suggestions for designing novel human-in-the-loop translation service systems aimed at optimizing service quality.
