AU  - Dong, Shuangyi
T3  - Aiiip '25
AB  - Reinforcement learning algorithms in the field of robotics are advancing rapidly, with their primary significance in robot control lying in training robots to learn skills autonomously. Instead of programmers telling a robot how to act, they only need to specify what task to accomplish, allowing the robot to learn the policy on its own. Because reinforcement learning learns through direct interaction with the environment, it can naturally adapt to noise and uncertainty during the training process, endowing the robot with strong adaptability and robustness. However, designing an appropriate reward function is exceptionally difficult, a challenge that often stems from the complexity of the robot’s environment, the unintuitive nature of its actions, or the absence of a concrete objective, all of which make the manual design and tuning of reward functions a formidable task. Today’s Large Language Models (LLMs) possess powerful contextual understanding capabilities; by processing inputs like the environment’s source code and human-provided descriptions, they can quickly and accurately comprehend the specific details of the environment. Simultaneously, their powerful programming and reasoning abilities enable them to rapidly design reward functions based on a proposed task objective and to infer the deficiencies of the current reward function from training results for continuous modification and iteration. Therefore, I conceived the idea of leveraging a large language model to design and iteratively update reward functions. The work presented in this paper is conducted within the Bipedal Walker-v3 environment from OpenAI Gymnasium, utilizing a large language model to design and fine-tune a reward function with the ultimate goal of training a simulated robot to walk upright on two feet in a human-like manner.
