TI  - A conceptual framework for an LLM-powered multimodal affective tutoring system for programming education
AU  - Qing, Shan
AU  - Chen, Liangwei
T3  - Eki '25
AB  - Current Large Language Model (LLM) based Intelligent Tutoring Systems (ITS) exhibit significant limitations in their capacity to perceive and respond to learners' emotional states. While these systems demonstrate advanced capabilities in delivering cognitive-level feedback, particularly in programming education, they largely overlook affective and motivational factors that are critical to learning success. This gap is particularly problematic for novice programmers who experience high frustration levels and cognitive load. This paper proposes the Multimodal Affective Tutoring System (MATS). This conceptual framework addresses this limitation by systematically integrating real-time multimodal data streams, including code analysis, facial expressions, and vocal prosody. The framework constructs comprehensive, dynamic learner models that inform an LLM-based pedagogical core, enabling the delivery of both precise cognitive support and empathic, affect-aware interventions. MATS represents a paradigm shift toward personalized, human-centered learning experiences designed to improve student persistence and success in programming education. The framework's theoretical foundation and architectural design provide a blueprint for developing next-generation intelligent tutoring systems that recognize emotion as a fundamental component of effective learning.
