AU  - Lu, Wenxin
AU  - Yang, Yuantao
AU  - Wei, Wenxia
AU  - Yin, Changsheng
T3  - Eitce '25
AB  - Applied Text is an important carrier and link for information dissemination and communication. With the increasing richness of production and life in human society, the diversity and complexity of applied text generation are becoming increasingly obvious. However, due to the limitations of subjective factors such as individual knowledge, work experience and time cost, manual writing inevitably has problems such as unreasonable framework and incomplete content. The birth of large language model has brought new opportunities for applied text generation. The large language model has the advantages of semantic understanding, text generation and information integration, and can assist in writing tasks such as literature search and framework construction. To solve the problem of how to scientifically integrate the applied text generation process and the function of the large language model, this paper introduces the event schema induction method, and proposes a human-computer collaborative writing mode based on the large language model, which consists of three steps: “passage retrieval - initial architecture extraction - item expansion”. Comparison experiment of human and machine writing shows that this method can significantly improve the writing efficiency and maximize the guarantee of reasonable framework and complete content of the document.
