AB  - The pursuit of intelligent and reliable autonomous systems has long been a central objective in artificial intelligence research. However, traditional agents often suffer from limited generalization, strong data dependency, and poor adaptability, making them inadequate in complex and dynamic environments. In recent years, the emergence of large language models (LLMs) has injected new vitality into this field. With their remarkable reasoning and planning abilities, LLMs are playing increasingly critical roles in intelligent agent systems, and their integration with agent architectures has become a prominent research hotspot. Existing studies have investigated task decomposition methods such as Chain of Thought and Tree of Thoughts, multi-agent collaboration frameworks, and unified workflow models for LLM-driven systems, providing new insights into agent design. Nevertheless, LLMs still face significant challenges in efficiency, controllability, and consistency. Despite these limitations, their potential in complex task planning and decision-making remains undeniable. This paper aims to systematically review the latest progress of LLM-based agents in task planning and decision-making, analyze their strengths and weaknesses, and offer perspectives to guide future research directions.
