AB  - Technological advancements are transforming global education. This study investigates how artificial intelligence (AI) can enhance intelligent teaching by focusing on students’ classroom postures through computer-human interaction (CHI). While computer vision technology enhances classroom monitoring, its real-world application to refine teaching lags. This study addresses this gap by utilizing monitoring devices and computer vision technology to design a posture detection scheme. Using the Open VINO model, the system predicts students’ postures, while the MQTT protocol enables remote data transmission. Visual observation devices recorded classrooms in China, detected postures such as standing, sitting, and hand-raising, provided feedback to teachers. With the design of a personalized feedback mechanism using Large Language Model (LLM), enabling AI and teachers to co-create the smart classroom. Our posture detection system fostering novel educator-student interactions within the CHI framework, ultimately driving educational progress.
