AU  - Wang, Dali
T3  - Iar '25
AB  - Accurate calculation and analysis of wellbore trajectories are fundamental to oil and gas drilling engineering, directly impacting operational safety and economic efficiency. This process currently relies heavily on commercial software with complex interfaces, presenting challenges such as high technical barriers and low analysis efficiency. To overcome these limitations, this paper proposes a novel conversational intelligent computation paradigm based on Large Language Models (LLMs). The system utilizes natural language as an interaction interface and adopts an innovative architecture comprising a Dialogue Engine, a Semantic Understanding Center, an Algorithm Executor, and a Data Coordinator to understand engineering computation intents and perform adaptive task planning. Two levels of validation tasks were designed: routine computation tasks and complex reasoning tasks. Results demonstrate that the system can not only accurately execute single instructions but also autonomously complete multi-step workflows with dependencies. This research provides a feasible technical pathway for low-barrier, high-efficiency, and intelligent analysis in well engineering, representing a significant practice of empowering industrial control systems with advanced algorithms.
