TY  - CONF
TI  - Evaluating fine-tuned GPT-4o on gravitational wave literature through cross-model QA benchmarking
AU  - Wei, Wei
AU  - Zhang, Fan
T3  - Eitce '25
AB  - Large Language Models (LLMs) have demonstrated impressive general-purpose capabilities, yet their effectiveness can diminish in highly specialized scientific domains. This paper evaluates a domain-tuned LLM, Coze (based on GPT-4o), fine-tuned on gravitational wave literature, in the context of astrophysical question answering. We benchmark Coze against three state-of-the-art general LLMs (Grok-3, Gemini, DeepSeek) on a set of domain-specific questions covering gravitational wave astrophysics. We assess whether ingesting expert literature improves the model's accuracy and depth in this domain. Coze and the baseline models were posed 100 questions spanning topics like interpreting figures, recalling experimental details, reasoning about gravitational-wave events, integrating knowledge across publications, and recognizing ambiguity in data. Domain experts judged the answers based on the correctness, completeness, formality, logic, and relevance of the answers. We demonstrate that the fine-tuned model has competitive or superior performance on various question type categories, particularly outperforming in questions that prompt the integration of cross-paper knowledge and dealing with ambiguous cases with professional attitude. Yet not all gains are consistent for all models: some general models do better than Coze for logical reasoning and shapes reasoning. We also talk about how these results affect the application of domain-specific LLMs to research. The paper demonstrates that through targeted fine-tuning, domain relevance and nuance can be incorporated into LLM responses, which allows them to be used as knowledgeable assistive agents in astrophysics.
