AB  - This doctoral research introduces ClarifAI, a web-based Asynchronous Online Focus Group (AOFG) platform that integrates a multi-agent ensemble of large language models (LLMs) to enhance the quality and interpretability of user feedback. The project addresses key limitations in traditional and online feedback methods, including social desirability bias, vague responses, and the challenges of conducting follow-up in asynchronous settings. By embedding automated laddering interviews and ensemble-based clarity classification into the AOFG platform, ClarifAI aims to facilitate richer, more actionable insights from participants. Initial experiments demonstrate promising results for synthetic feedback generation, clarity annotation, and human-model agreement. A working prototype of the AOFG platform is currently being piloted in a narrative AI study. Future work will evaluate the usability and effectiveness of the ensemble and laddering components in both simulated and real-world environments. This research contributes to HCI by advancing methods for remote qualitative data collection and collaborative AI reasoning in dynamic, user-centered contexts.
