TY  - CONF
TI  - Modelling and predicting user actions in conversational information retrieval
AU  - Fu, Xiao
AU  - Lipani, Aldo
AU  - Kando, Noriko
T3  - Ictir '25
AB  - Personalisation is pivotal in dialogue systems, such as conversational recommender systems and conversational search systems. With the significant advancements in large language models (LLMs), this paper focuses on the newly introduced iKAT 2023 dataset, which incorporates personalisation to study the application of LLMs in modelling and predicting user actions. Four LLMs were employed to annotate user actions, adhering to the same theoretical framework used by human annotators. Two additional LLMs were utilised to predict the forthcoming user actions. The findings reveal that LLMs, given the conversation context, are capable of labelling user actions with an F1 score of 0.63 and a Cohen's kappa of 0.53 across six action types. However, the efficacy of predicting user actions varied depending on the specific LLMs, the targeted actions, and the extent to which user profiles were integrated, with F1 scores ranging from 0.18 to 0.64 in different actions. These results underscore the potential of employing LLMs both to assist in labelling conversation data and in predicting user actions. The findings further substantiate a model for the conversational flow within the iKAT 2023 dataset. Further exploration of the conversation flows demonstrates the Reveal-Inquire pattern, which plays a significant role in modelling the conversation. The conversations labelled during this study: https://github.com/RichardFu123/model_predict_user_actions.
