TI  - Legal judgment prediction with LLM and graph contrastive learning networks
AU  - Xia, Yangbin
AU  - Luo, Xudong
T3  - Csai '24
AB  - Legal judgment prediction is a complex task that involves analysing case descriptions and relevant facts to predict outcomes. This paper presents LLG-Judger, a novel framework combining Large Language models and Graph neural networks for LJP. LLG-Judger integrates the strengths of rule-based divisions, Large Language Models (LLMs) for initial case predictions, and graph neural networks for structured fact representation. The proposed model first constructs a fact graph from case descriptions and then applies a graph encoder to capture syntactic and semantic relationships within the text. To enhance prediction accuracy, we employ a contrastive learning module that improves feature representation by focusing on both syntactic and global semantic neighbours. Additionally, we integrate ChatGPT’s predictions with the graph model’s results using KL divergence to optimise the final prediction. Experimental evaluations demonstrate the effectiveness of LLG-Judger, achieving superior performance over various baselines, especially in the legal domain.
